What exactly is sensors_event_t : It is a custom C++ struct. Used to store different quantities of various sensors at different snapshots of time:
It contains empty slots for:Acceleration ($x, y, z$)Magnetic field ($x, y, z$)Gyroscope rotation ($x, y, z$)Temperature, pressure, light, etc.

Adafruit_Sensor* s: This is a pointer to an object. Instead of writing a separate function for an accelerometer, a gyroscope, and a magnetometer,
this function accepts a generic sensor pointer s. You can pass any supported sensor into this function, and it will handle it.
The sensors_event_t event is an empty slot. It is not filled yet.
Only in this line is the slots of quantities getting written - s-> getEvent(&event);

We need sensor.begin(hex address) for every I2C sensor because -> the code will make the mcu to start the sda channel and also if sensor.begin(hex address) is true, then it 
is guarantee that the sensor is connecetd to mcu. 
Note: The hexadecimal device address exists only for I2C sensor.

There are 127 possible address : from 1 to 127.
To get the hex address of the sensor we are using we can do it by coding:
Wire.beginTransmission(address) will make the mcu send start condition in sda alongwith 7 bit binary address.
After sending the start condition, SDA will go to HIGH. If there is any sensor in that address, it will pull the sda to low. This is confirmation called ACK
If no sensor in address, then SDA is at HIGH, this is called NACK
















